select
  s.id, 'board', NULL, 'Basic science: fluid + electrolyte management

คำถาม: postoperative IV fluid + electrolyte management', '[{"label":"A","text":"Liberal IV fluid for all postop"},{"label":"B","text":"**Postoperative fluid management — goal-directed restrictive trend**: (1) **Fluid types**: - **Crystalloid**: balanced solutions (Lactated Ringer''s, Plasma-Lyte) preferred over 0.9% NSS for resuscitation (avoid hyperchloremic acidosis); 5% dextrose for hypoglycemia adjunct; - **Colloid**: albumin (5% for resuscitation in selected — septic shock per Surviving Sepsis 2021); HES (hydroxyethyl starch) no longer recommended (renal injury + mortality); gelatins; - **Blood products** for specific indications; (2) **Goal-directed fluid therapy (GDT)**: - Avoid both over-resuscitation (third spacing, edema, ileus, anastomotic, ARDS) AND under-resuscitation (organ hypoperfusion); - Dynamic measures of fluid responsiveness: passive leg raise (PLR), pulse pressure variation (PPV), stroke volume variation (SVV), POCUS; - CVP no longer recommended as fluid responsiveness predictor; - Targets: MAP > 65, lactate clearance, UO 0.5 mL/kg/hr (caution in over-resuscitating just to UO); (3) **ERAS principles** for fluid: - Pre-op: no prolonged NPO (clear fluid up to 2h), carb loading 2h pre-op (improves insulin sensitivity); - Intra-op: balanced solutions, restrictive but adequate; avoid ''over-the-top'' fluid; - Post-op: oral intake as soon as tolerated; minimize maintenance IV; goal euvolemia; (4) **RELIEF trial (Myles NEJM 2018)** — restrictive (low) vs liberal (higher) fluid in major abdominal surgery: restrictive associated with more AKI; modern recommendation: moderate (not extreme either way) goal-directed; (5) **Electrolyte management postop**: - **Sodium**: monitor; both hyponatremia (overhydration with hypotonic) + hypernatremia possible - **Potassium**: monitor; K losses from NG, diarrhea, diuretic, alkalosis; replete carefully (max 10 mEq/h peripheral, 20 mEq/h central with monitoring) - **Magnesium**: often low postop; replete (Mg essential for K + Ca regulation, neuromuscular, cardiac) - **Calcium**: hypocalcemia post-thyroid/parathyroid surgery; transfusion (citrate); replete - **Phosphate**: refeeding syndrome, depletion; (6) **Glycemic control**: target 140-180 (avoid both extreme hyper + hypoglycemia); insulin sliding scale + correction; long-acting basal + bolus for outpatient regimens; (7) **Acid-base disorders postop**: - Metabolic acidosis: lactate (perfusion), hyperchloremia (NSS over-use), ketone (NPO, DKA) - Metabolic alkalosis: NG suction, vomiting, diuretic - Respiratory: hypoventilation (opioid, pain, sedation), hyperventilation (anxiety, pain, sepsis); (8) **Special situations**: - Cardiac surgery — pulmonary edema risk - Major liver resection — coagulopathy, hypoalbumin, ascites - Bariatric — dumping, dehydration - Sepsis — initial resuscitation 30 mL/kg crystalloid then goal-directed; (9) **Monitoring**: weight daily (most accurate volume change), I/O, electrolytes daily or more, hemodynamics, end-organ perfusion (UO, lactate, mental status)"},{"label":"C","text":"No fluid management needed"},{"label":"D","text":"TPN for all postop"},{"label":"E","text":"Fluid restriction always"}]'::jsonb,
  'B', '**Perioperative fluid + electrolyte management** — fundamental + has evolved significantly. Major shift from ''liberal'' to ''restrictive moderate'' (goal-directed). **Crystalloid selection**: - **Balanced (LR, Plasma-Lyte)** preferred over **0.9% NaCl** (normal saline) for resuscitation - NS large volumes → hyperchloremic acidosis, AKI risk (SMART, SALT-ED trials) - LR contains some K (4 mEq/L) — caution in hyperkalemia; safe in most - D5W for hypoglycemia/hypernatremia adjunct **Colloid use**: - **Albumin** — selected (e.g., large volume paracentesis, hepatorenal syndrome, septic shock per Surviving Sepsis; no general benefit over crystalloid per SAFE trial) - **HES (hydroxyethyl starch)** — NOT recommended (CHEST, 6S trials — increased renal injury + mortality) - **Gelatins** — limited use, expensive, no superior outcomes **Goal-directed therapy**: avoid both extremes; dynamic measures preferred over static (CVP, urine output alone). **ERAS fluid principles**: - No prolonged NPO (clear fluid up to 2h) - Carb loading 2h pre-op - Moderate intraoperative (balanced solutions) - Early oral intake postop - Minimize maintenance IV when oral OK **Restrictive vs liberal** — RELIEF trial (Myles NEJM 2018): restrictive fluid in major abdominal surgery associated with more AKI vs slightly liberal; modern consensus: moderate goal-directed (not extreme either way). **Electrolyte considerations postop**: - Na: monitor; hyponatremia from hypotonic fluid + SIADH common postop; hypernatremia from dehydration - K: NG losses, diuretic; replete carefully - Mg: low common; impacts K + Ca + cardiac; replete IV - Ca: post-thyroid/parathyroid; transfusion (citrate) - PO4: refeeding syndrome **Refeeding syndrome**: severely malnourished resuming feeds → PO4 + Mg + K drop into cells; cardiac + neuromuscular dysfunction; thiamine deficiency manifests. Prevent: gradual feed advancement + thiamine pre-feed + electrolyte monitoring + replacement. **Acid-base**: assess Anion Gap; common postop disorders: metabolic acidosis (lactic, hyperchloremic), metabolic alkalosis (NG, vomiting), respiratory acidosis (hypoventilation). **Glycemic**: target 140-180; hyperglycemia + hypoglycemia both bad; use insulin sliding scale + correction. **Special**: cardiac surgery (pulmonary edema risk; restrictive); liver resection (coagulopathy, ascites, hypoalbumin); bariatric (dumping, dehydration risk).', NULL,
  'easy', 'renal_gu', 'review',
  'surgery', 'basic_science', 'renal_gu', 'adult',
  'ERAS Society Fluid Therapy; Myles PS et al. NEJM 2018 (RELIEF); Semler MW et al. NEJM 2018 (SMART); Surviving Sepsis 2021', 'AI-generated-board-seed', true, 'seeded via Claude Code session (no critique pass)'
from public.mcq_subjects s
