select
  s.id, 'board', NULL, 'Basic science: cardiac arrest + cardiopulmonary resuscitation in surgical patient

คำถาม: post-cardiac surgery cardiac arrest — special protocol', '[{"label":"A","text":"Standard ACLS only"},{"label":"B","text":"**Cardiac Arrest after Cardiac Surgery (CALS) Protocol — modified ACLS**: (1) **Critical differences from standard ACLS**: - Recent thoracotomy + sternotomy + intracardiac/great vessel anatomy - Resternotomy with internal cardiac massage if external CPR fails - Specific arrest etiologies — VF, tamponade, bleeding, ischemia, hypovolemia, pacemaker; (2) **Immediate response within 5 minutes** (modified ACLS): - Confirm arrest - Call for help + arrest team + perfusionist (CPB on standby) - Begin chest compressions (caution with sternotomy site / wires) - Defibrillate VF/VT (3 shocks before drug if witnessed in monitored ICU) - Pacing if asystole / bradycardia + pacemaker available (post-op patients often have epicardial wires); (3) **Specific etiologic management**: - **Tamponade** — open chest within 5 min if PEA / ineffective CPR (life-saving) - **Hemorrhage** — open chest, identify + control source, transfuse - **Tension pneumothorax** — decompress - **Hypovolemia** — fluid + blood - **Hyperkalemia** — Ca + insulin + glucose - **MI / graft thrombosis** — emergent intervention; (4) **Resternotomy**: - Indications: VF/VT unresponsive 3 shocks, PEA without reversible cause, asystole, suspected tamponade - Within 5 min of arrest to maximize survival - Internal cardiac massage 100/min, defibrillation internal, identify cause - All ICUs caring for post-cardiac surgery patients should have resternotomy capability; (5) **Drugs in CALS**: - Avoid epinephrine bolus initially (can cause severe HTN + intracardiac complications) - Use vasopressin / norepi infusion - Amiodarone, lidocaine for VF/VT; (6) **Extracorporeal life support (ECMO / ECLS)**: - VA-ECMO bridge for refractory - Cannulation femoral + peripheral or central - Improved outcomes with rapid deployment; (7) **Outcomes** with CALS protocol — survival higher (50%+) than standard ACLS in cardiac surgery patients due to addressing surgical etiology + resternotomy; (8) **Training + drills** — STS CALS course + simulation; ICU + OR teams should be familiar; (9) **Documentation + debrief**: M&M, learnings, prevention; family communication"},{"label":"C","text":"Do not perform CPR"},{"label":"D","text":"Use general anesthesia for resuscitation"},{"label":"E","text":"Wait for cardiologist"}]'::jsonb,
  'B', '**Cardiac Arrest after Cardiac Surgery (CALS)** — distinct protocol per Society of Thoracic Surgeons (STS) due to unique pathophysiology + therapeutic opportunities. **Why different from standard ACLS**: - Specific etiologies (tamponade 35%, hemorrhage 25%, VF/VT 25%, MI/graft, tension pneumothorax, hyperkalemia, pacemaker failure) - Recent thoracotomy + sternotomy enables internal cardiac massage + visualization - Standard chest compressions may injure surgical site - Epicardial pacing wires often available - Goal: identify + treat specific cause within 5 min to optimize outcome **Key steps (STS CALS Protocol)**: 1. Within 1 min: confirm arrest, call for help (arrest team + perfusion) 2. VF/VT (witnessed monitored ICU): 3 shocks immediately, then chest compressions 3. Asystole / severe bradycardia: pace with epicardial wires if available 4. PEA: think of reversible causes (tamponade, tension pneumothorax, hypovolemia, hyperkalemia) 5. **Resternotomy within 5 min** if: - VF/VT after 3 shocks - PEA without reversible cause identified - Persistent arrest > 5 min - Suspected tamponade or active bleeding 6. Internal cardiac massage during open exploration 7. Identify + treat cause: control bleeding, evacuate tamponade, repair injury, ECMO if cardiogenic shock **Drug differences**: - Avoid bolus epinephrine (severe HTN, intracardiac complications) - Use vasopressin or norepi infusion - Amiodarone for VF/VT - Calcium for hyperkalemia / Ca channel blocker toxicity **ECMO / ECLS**: bridge to recovery / transplant; rapid deployment improves survival in refractory. **Outcomes**: CALS protocol implementation improves survival from cardiac arrest after cardiac surgery to ~ 50%+ (vs 17% standard ACLS). **Training**: STS publishes CALS course + simulation curriculum; ICU + OR teams should be familiar + drilled.', NULL,
  'hard', 'cardiovascular', 'review',
  'surgery', 'basic_science', 'cardiovascular', 'adult',
