select
  s.id, 'board', NULL, 'ผู้ป่วยอายุ 40 ปี post-living-donor liver transplant 5 ปี for HCC + HBV cirrhosis — มา outpatient clinic for routine surveillance + planning for second pregnancy

Lab: stable graft function, HBV DNA undetectable on antiviral, immunosuppression on low-dose tacrolimus monotherapy

คำถาม: integrative survivorship + reproductive planning', '[{"label":"A","text":"No special considerations"},{"label":"B","text":"**Post-liver transplant survivorship + planning pregnancy — integrative care**: (1) **Multidisciplinary clinic**: transplant hepatology, transplant surgery, MFM (maternal-fetal medicine), obstetrics, pharmacy, social work, mental health; (2) **Pre-conception counseling**: - Timing: ≥ 1-2 years post-transplant with stable graft function + immunosuppression - Stable lab parameters: normal LFT, stable creatinine, no rejection in 6-12 months - Medication review + adjustment (see below) - Disease control (HBV undetectable, HCC surveillance) - Maternal health optimization (BMI, BP, glycemic, vaccines) - Genetic counseling if disease has heritable component; (3) **Immunosuppression in pregnancy**: - **Tacrolimus** — safe in pregnancy; clearance increases — may need dose increase (monitor levels) - **Cyclosporine** — safe alternative; similar - **Azathioprine** — safe in pregnancy + breastfeeding (despite black box warning, evidence supports safety for fetus) - **Mycophenolate (MMF, MPA)** — TERATOGENIC — fetal loss + congenital anomalies (cleft, ear, cardiac) — STOP 6 weeks before conception + use alternative (azathioprine) - **mTOR inhibitors (sirolimus, everolimus)** — limited data; preferable to avoid; switch if possible - **Steroids** — low-dose acceptable - **Belatacept** — limited data - **Antivirals (entecavir, tenofovir for HBV)** — tenofovir preferred in pregnancy (better safety data); continue; (4) **HBV-specific considerations**: - Continue antiviral suppression - Tenofovir preferred (TDF or TAF) over entecavir in pregnancy - HBV transmission to neonate: HBIG + HBV vaccine at birth + appropriate maternal viral suppression - Monitor maternal viral load + LFT - HCC surveillance continues; (5) **HCC surveillance**: - 5-yr post-transplant: AFP + imaging (US/CT/MRI) q6-12 mo standard for transplanted HCC - Lifelong surveillance; (6) **Pregnancy management** (high-risk): - Increased risks: HT, GDM, preeclampsia, preterm birth, SGA, miscarriage, abruption, infection - Multidisciplinary high-risk OB - Increased fetal surveillance + maternal monitoring - Vaccinations updated (acellular pertussis Tdap, influenza inactivated) - Avoid live vaccines (yellow fever, MMR, varicella); (7) **Delivery planning**: - Vaginal delivery preferred when feasible - Cesarean for obstetric indications - Anti-rejection medication continued throughout - Stress-dose steroids may be needed - Antibiotic prophylaxis if cesarean (standard); (8) **Postpartum**: - Continue immunosuppression - Lactation: most immunosuppressants compatible (tacrolimus, cyclosporine, azathioprine, prednisone); mycophenolate AVOID - Postpartum surveillance for rejection (immune changes post-delivery) - HCC surveillance resumes per schedule; (9) **Family planning + contraception**: - During fertile years + spacing pregnancies - Reliable methods; IUD (copper preferred over hormonal — controversial efficacy in immunosuppressed; reasonable); barrier; permanent if family complete; (10) **Long-term**: continue lifelong post-transplant care; family + caregiver support; psychological wellbeing"},{"label":"C","text":"Stop all medications during pregnancy"},{"label":"D","text":"Refuse to allow pregnancy"},{"label":"E","text":"Discontinue HBV antiviral"}]'::jsonb,
  'B', '**Pregnancy after liver transplant** — increasingly common as transplant outcomes improve. **Pre-conception planning**: - ≥ 1-2 years post-transplant - Stable graft function (LFT, Cr, immunosuppression levels) - No rejection within 6-12 months - Disease-specific control (HBV, HCV, autoimmune all in remission) - HCC: appropriate surveillance + acceptable disease-free interval (lifelong surveillance) **Immunosuppression in pregnancy** — major modifications: 1. **Tacrolimus**: CONTINUE; pregnancy-safe; clearance ↑ → may need dose increase (level monitoring) 2. **Cyclosporine**: CONTINUE; alternative to tacrolimus; safe 3. **Azathioprine**: CONTINUE — despite black box warning, evidence supports fetal safety 4. **Prednisone / methylprednisolone**: low-dose CONTINUE; safe 5. **Mycophenolate (MMF, MPA)**: STOP — TERATOGENIC (cleft palate, microtia, congenital heart, fetal loss); switch to azathioprine ≥ 6 weeks pre-conception 6. **mTOR inhibitors (sirolimus, everolimus)**: limited data; switch off if possible 7. **Belatacept**: limited data **Specific disease considerations**: - **HBV**: continue antiviral suppression; **tenofovir TDF/TAF preferred** in pregnancy (entecavir limited data); newborn HBIG + HBV vaccine; maternal viral load monitoring - **HCV**: cured most patients with DAAs; if active — defer pregnancy until treated - **Autoimmune (PBC, PSC, AIH)**: continue azathioprine; monitor flares - **NASH/MASH**: weight management - **HCC**: continued surveillance regardless of pregnancy **Maternal complications increased**: HT, preeclampsia, GDM, infection, anemia, preterm birth, bleeding (cesarean), graft dysfunction risk. **Fetal complications increased**: prematurity, IUGR/SGA, lower birth weight, miscarriage (some studies); congenital anomalies usually not increased (with appropriate medication management). **Surveillance during pregnancy**: more frequent OB visits, fetal monitoring (growth, biophysical), maternal labs (LFT, Cr, drug levels, glucose, viral load). **Delivery**: vaginal preferred when feasible; cesarean for obstetric indications; routine perioperative antibiotic; anesthesia consult. **Lactation compatibility**: tacrolimus, cyclosporine, azathioprine, prednisone, hydroxychloroquine all generally compatible (modify per Lactmed); mycophenolate AVOID. **Contraception** during transplant + between pregnancies: reliable + safe — IUD (copper or hormonal), barrier, hormonal (caution with drug interactions), permanent if family complete.', NULL,
  'hard', 'obgyn', 'review',
  'surgery', 'integrative', 'obgyn', 'adult',
  'AST Consensus Conference Pregnancy + Transplantation; AASLD Pregnancy + Liver Disease; Coscia LA et al. Clin Transplant', 'AI-generated-board-seed', true, 'seeded via Claude Code session (no critique pass)'
from public.mcq_subjects s
where s.name = 'surg_integrative'
  and s.audience = 'board'
