select
  s.id, 'board', NULL, 'ทารกแรกเกิดอายุ 1 วัน born term, มาด้วย abdominal wall defect — bowel + liver exposed ที่ midline ไม่มี covering membrane

คำถาม: distinguish + management', '[{"label":"A","text":"Same as omphalocele"},{"label":"B","text":"**Gastroschisis vs Omphalocele — distinct entities**: **Gastroschisis**: defect right of umbilicus (paraumbilical), NO covering membrane, bowel exposed (often inflamed/thickened from amniotic fluid exposure), umbilical cord normal position, LOW association with other anomalies (5-10%) but high bowel atresia; **Omphalocele**: midline defect at umbilical cord, COVERED by amnion + peritoneum membrane (may rupture), liver + bowel inside sac, HIGH association with chromosomal (trisomy 13, 18, 21) + cardiac anomalies (30-50%), Beckwith-Wiedemann, pentalogy of Cantrell; **Management of gastroschisis**: (1) Immediate: cover exposed bowel with sterile saline-soaked gauze + cling wrap or bowel bag; NPO, NG decompression, IV fluid (large losses), IV antibiotic, thermoregulation (high losses → hypothermia); (2) Operative — primary closure if abdominal cavity can accommodate (no compartment syndrome); OR staged with **silo** (preformed silastic silo or surgical silo) → daily reduction over 5-10 days → delayed closure; (3) Post-op: TPN until bowel function returns (often weeks), gradual enteral feeds; (4) Complications: short gut syndrome, motility disorders, atresia (concurrent), feeding intolerance; (5) Omphalocele management: similar staged approach but slower (large defects); ''paint + wait'' (silver sulfadiazine, escharification) for giant defects; sac itself protects; associated anomaly workup essential (echo, karyotype, etc.); (6) Long-term: most do well; nutritional + developmental follow-up"},{"label":"C","text":"Observation only"},{"label":"D","text":"Discharge home"},{"label":"E","text":"Total bowel resection"}]'::jsonb,
  'B', '**Abdominal wall defects** — two main: **Gastroschisis** vs **Omphalocele**. Differentiation critical for management + prognosis. Gastroschisis: right paraumbilical, no sac, inflamed bowel, fewer associations, primary or staged silo closure. Omphalocele: midline, intact sac, liver + bowel, MANY associated anomalies (cardiac 30-50%, chromosomal — trisomies, Beckwith-Wiedemann, Cantrell pentalogy), echo + karyotype workup essential. Both need NG decompression, IV fluid, thermoregulation, antibiotic, and surgical management (primary or staged silo). Outcomes generally good with modern care; long-term issues: feeding, growth, motility, short gut if extensive bowel resection.', NULL,
  'medium', 'pediatrics', 'review',
  'surgery', 'clinical_decision', 'pediatrics', 'peds',
  'APSA Pediatric Surgery Handbook; Christison-Lagay ER et al. Semin Pediatr Surg', 'AI-generated-board-seed', true, 'seeded via Claude Code session (no critique pass)'
from public.mcq_subjects s
where s.name = 'surg_clinical_decision'
  and s.audience = 'board'
  and not exists (
    select 1 from public.mcq_questions q
    where q.exam_source = 'AI-generated-board-seed'
      and q.board_specialty = 'surgery'
      and q.scenario = 'ทารกแรกเกิดอายุ 1 วัน born term, มาด้วย abdominal wall defect — bowel + liver exposed ที่ midline ไม่มี covering membrane

