select
  s.id, 'board', NULL, 'Basic science: immunology + transplant

คำถาม: organ rejection mechanisms + immunosuppression', '[{"label":"A","text":"Rejection cannot be prevented"},{"label":"B","text":"**Transplant rejection mechanisms + immunosuppression**: (1) **Types of rejection**: - **Hyperacute** (minutes-hours): preformed antibodies (ABO incompatibility, HLA mismatch) → complement + thrombosis; modern era rare (crossmatch screening); treatment: graft removal - **Acute cellular (T-cell mediated)**: days-weeks; T-cells recognize donor MHC; treatable with steroid + ATG; tubulitis + interstitial infiltrate (kidney) - **Acute antibody-mediated (AMR)**: B-cell + antibody mediated; weeks-months; C4d deposition + DSA; harder treatment (plasmapheresis + IVIG + rituximab + bortezomib) - **Chronic rejection** (months-years): combined immune + non-immune; obliterative arteriopathy, fibrosis; harder to reverse; gradual graft dysfunction; (2) **HLA + immune recognition**: - HLA Class I (A, B, C) — most cells - HLA Class II (DR, DQ, DP) — antigen-presenting cells - Direct + indirect alloantigen recognition - Crossmatch testing (CDC + flow + virtual) pre-transplant essential - DSA (donor-specific antibodies) — risk of AMR; (3) **Immunosuppression categories**: a. **Induction** (peri-transplant): - **Antibody therapy**: anti-thymocyte globulin (ATG — polyclonal T-cell depleting), basiliximab (anti-IL-2 receptor), alemtuzumab (anti-CD52, more depleting) - **Steroid bolus**: methylprednisolone b. **Maintenance** (lifelong): - **Calcineurin inhibitors (CNI)**: tacrolimus, cyclosporine — backbone; nephrotoxicity major side effect - **Antimetabolites**: mycophenolate (MMF, MPA) > azathioprine - **Steroids**: prednisone (often tapered to low-dose or stopped) - **mTOR inhibitors**: sirolimus, everolimus — anti-tumor; SE: poor wound healing, pneumonitis, mouth ulcers, hyperlipidemia - **Costimulation blockade**: belatacept (CD80/86) c. **Rejection treatment**: - Acute cellular: pulse steroid + ATG - AMR: plasmapheresis + IVIG + rituximab + bortezomib/daratumumab - Refractory: alemtuzumab; (4) **Side effects of immunosuppression** to manage: - Infection (opportunistic — CMV, PJP, fungal; bacterial; reactivation HBV) - Malignancy (skin, PTLD, increased cancer risk overall) - Cardiovascular (HT, hyperlipidemia, DM) - Renal (CNI nephrotoxicity) - Neurological (tremor, headache, CNI neurotoxicity, PRES) - Hematologic (cytopenias) - Metabolic (NODAT — new-onset DM after transplant) - Bone (osteoporosis from steroid); (5) **Therapeutic drug monitoring**: tacrolimus, cyclosporine, sirolimus, mycophenolate levels; (6) **Tolerance** — holy grail: mixed chimerism, regulatory T cells, donor BM transplant + organ — experimental; clinical trials ongoing; (7) **Long-term**: cancer surveillance, infection prophylaxis, cardiovascular risk, drug interactions awareness; adherence support"},{"label":"C","text":"No immunosuppression needed"},{"label":"D","text":"Single agent for life"},{"label":"E","text":"Cure tolerance achievable for all"}]'::jsonb,
  'B', '**Transplant immunology + immunosuppression** — foundational. **Types of rejection**: 1. **Hyperacute**: minutes-hours; preformed Ab; ABO + HLA mismatch; thrombosis; graft loss — prevented by crossmatch 2. **Acute cellular (TCMR)**: T-cell mediated; days-months; treatable with pulse steroid 3. **Acute antibody-mediated (AMR)**: B-cell + Ab; days-months; harder treatment (PEX, IVIG, rituximab) 4. **Chronic**: months-years; multifactorial; gradual graft loss **HLA Class I (A, B, C)** all nucleated cells. **HLA Class II (DR, DQ, DP)** APCs (B cells, macrophages, dendritic). **Alloantigen recognition**: direct (donor APC presenting donor HLA to recipient T cell) + indirect (recipient APC processing donor antigen). **Pre-transplant testing**: ABO, HLA, PRA (panel reactive antibodies), crossmatch (CDC, flow, virtual), DSA assessment. **Immunosuppression — 3 phases**: 1. **Induction** (peri-op): - ATG (T-cell depleting, polyclonal) - Basiliximab (anti-IL2R, less depleting) - Alemtuzumab (anti-CD52, profound depletion) - Methylprednisolone bolus 2. **Maintenance** (lifelong, ''triple therapy'' common): - CNI (tacrolimus > cyclosporine) — backbone - Antiproliferative (mycophenolate > azathioprine) - Steroid (prednisone — often tapered) - Alternatives: mTOR inhibitor (sirolimus, everolimus), belatacept 3. **Rejection treatment**: - Acute cellular: pulse steroid + ATG - AMR: plasmapheresis + IVIG + rituximab ± bortezomib + steroids **Side effect profile** (major considerations): - Tacrolimus: nephrotoxic, neurotoxic, NODAT, HT, tremor, hair loss, hyperK - Cyclosporine: similar + hirsutism, gum hyperplasia - Mycophenolate: GI, leukopenia, anemia, teratogenic - Sirolimus: wound healing impaired, pneumonitis, hyperlipidemia, mouth ulcers - Steroids: HT, DM, osteoporosis, cataract, weight, mood, AVN - Belatacept: PTLD risk (especially EBV-naive recipient) **Therapeutic drug monitoring**: trough levels (tacrolimus, cyclosporine, sirolimus, everolimus); higher targets early post-transplant, lower later. **Tolerance** — operational tolerance without immunosuppression: holy grail; mixed chimerism (Stanford, Mass Gen + others) achieving partial success in selected; not clinical routine yet.', NULL,
  'medium', 'id', 'review',
  'surgery', 'basic_science', 'id', 'adult',
  'AST/ASTS Immunosuppression Guidelines; OPTN/UNOS; Halloran PF NEJM', 'AI-generated-board-seed', true, 'seeded via Claude Code session (no critique pass)'
from public.mcq_subjects s
where s.name = 'surg_basic_science'
