select
  s.id, 'board', NULL, 'Basic science: surgical decision-making + evidence-based medicine

คำถาม: evidence-based surgery + clinical practice guidelines', '[{"label":"A","text":"Personal preference only"},{"label":"B","text":"**Evidence-Based Surgery — principles + application**: (1) **Hierarchy of evidence** (highest → lowest): - Systematic reviews + meta-analyses of RCTs - RCTs (large, well-designed) - Cohort studies (prospective > retrospective) - Case-control studies - Case series - Case reports - Expert opinion / textbook (NB: hierarchy not absolute — well-conducted observational with large effect > poor RCT); (2) **Surgical evidence challenges**: - RCTs in surgery harder than medical (sham surgery ethics, learning curve, surgeon variability) - Crossover difficult - Equipoise variable - Blinding nearly impossible - Quality variation - Volume + experience effects; (3) **Clinical Practice Guidelines (CPG)** — synthesize evidence: - **GRADE methodology**: assess quality of evidence (high, moderate, low, very low) + strength of recommendation (strong vs conditional/weak) - Major surgical societies: ACS, SAGES, ASCRS, AAST, EAST, WSES, NCCN, SVS, AHPBA, ESC, etc. - International + regional adaptations; (4) **Apply evidence to patient** — EBM cycle: - **Ask** focused clinical question (PICO: Patient, Intervention, Comparison, Outcome) - **Acquire** best evidence - **Appraise** validity + relevance - **Apply** to patient (considering values + circumstances) - **Assess** + reflect on outcomes; (5) **Shared decision-making**: - Patient preferences + values matter - Especially for elective / quality-of-life decisions - Decision aids (Ottawa, Mayo Choice) - Outcomes-focused conversation; (6) **Variation in practice**: - Substantial unwarranted variation in surgical decisions (Dartmouth Atlas) - Quality improvement to reduce variation when evidence clear; (7) **Quality improvement**: - ACS NSQIP — risk-adjusted outcomes benchmark - STS, MBSAQIP, MIPS, others - PDSA cycles, FMEA, RCA - Audit + feedback (Cochrane evidence supports); (8) **Research integration**: - Clinical trial enrollment - Translational research - Implementation science (closing evidence-to-practice gap — Cochrane EPOC); (9) **Critical appraisal**: - Internal validity: bias, confounding, randomization, blinding, ITT analysis - External validity: generalizability to your patient population - Magnitude of effect + clinical relevance - Cost-effectiveness; (10) **Beyond efficacy — patient-reported outcomes (PROs)**: - Quality of life - Functional outcomes - Patient satisfaction - Long-term implications - Capturing what matters to patients"},{"label":"C","text":"Ignore patient preferences"},{"label":"D","text":"Use only personal experience"},{"label":"E","text":"No quality measurement needed"}]'::jsonb,
  'B', '**Evidence-Based Surgery** — synthesis of best evidence + clinical expertise + patient values. **Hierarchy of evidence**: meta-analysis > RCT > cohort > case-control > case series > case report > expert opinion. Not absolute — methodologic quality + applicability also matter. **GRADE methodology** (Grading of Recommendations Assessment, Development + Evaluation) — used by WHO + many guidelines: assess quality (high → moderate → low → very low) + strength (strong / conditional) of recommendations. **Surgical research challenges**: - RCT difficult (sham surgery ethics, learning curve, surgeon variability, blinding hard) - Observational + registry data often important - IDEAL framework (Idea → Development → Exploration → Assessment → Long-term study) for surgical innovation evaluation **EBM cycle (PICO + 5 A''s)**: 1. Ask focused question (PICO) 2. Acquire evidence 3. Appraise critically 4. Apply to patient 5. Assess + reflect **Shared decision-making**: - Patient values + preferences part of EBM definition - Decision aids - Especially important: elective, quality-of-life, preference-sensitive conditions (e.g., BPH treatment, prostate cancer, knee replacement, bariatric surgery) **Critical appraisal**: - Internal validity: randomization, allocation concealment, blinding, ITT, attrition - External validity: generalizability - Effect size + confidence interval - NNT (number needed to treat) - Cost-effectiveness **Major guideline organizations**: ACS, SAGES, ASCRS, AAST, EAST, WSES, NCCN, SVS, AHPBA, ESC, ESVS, AHA/ACC, ATS, RCOG, ACOG, AAP. **Quality improvement**: - ACS NSQIP — gold standard for surgical outcomes benchmarking - STS Database (cardiothoracic) - MBSAQIP (bariatric) - MIPS (Medicare quality reporting) - Process measures (SCIP, WHO checklist) - Outcomes measures - Patient-reported outcomes (PROs) **Implementation science**: closing evidence-practice gap — getting proven interventions into routine practice. Cochrane EPOC (Effective Practice + Organization of Care). **Volume-outcome relationship**: higher-volume surgeons + hospitals → better outcomes for complex procedures (Whipple, esophagectomy, hepatectomy, complex cardiac); regionalization of complex surgery debated.', NULL,
  'easy', 'procedures', 'review',
  'surgery', 'basic_science', 'procedures', 'adult',
  'Sackett DL et al. (EBM); Cochrane Handbook; GRADE Working Group; ACS Clinical Congress Education', 'AI-generated-board-seed', true, 'seeded via Claude Code session (no critique pass)'
from public.mcq_subjects s
where s.name = 'surg_basic_science'
