select
  s.id, 'board', NULL, 'ผู้ป่วยอายุ 65 ปี post-renal transplant 2 ปี on tacrolimus + MMF + low-dose pred; รอบล่าสุด PCR EBV viremia + new neck lymphadenopathy + LDH elevated

Lymph node biopsy: polymorphic B-cell proliferation, EBV-positive
CT: multiple lymphadenopathy + spleen enlarged + slight liver lesion

คำถาม: management of PTLD', '[{"label":"A","text":"Continue immunosuppression same"},{"label":"B","text":"**Post-Transplant Lymphoproliferative Disorder (PTLD) — EBV-driven; multimodal**: (1) **Reduce immunosuppression first-line** — restores immune control: - Reduce CNI by 25-50% - Stop antimetabolite (MMF) - Maintain low-dose steroid - Goal: shrink lymphoma without losing graft - Single most important first intervention; (2) **Rituximab (anti-CD20)** monotherapy for early lesions: - Single agent first per RAR risk-adapted protocol - Response 50-60% - Tolerable; (3) **R-CHOP or other chemotherapy** for: - Polymorphic/monomorphic PTLD not responding to RI + rituximab - Aggressive disease - Bulky disease - Risk: graft loss with chemo myelosuppression + immunosuppression reduction; (4) **EBV-specific T-cell therapy** — emerging: - Cytotoxic T-lymphocytes (CTL) — third-party EBV-CTL banks (Tabelecleucel for EBV-PTLD post-HCT/SOT; FDA-approved 2024) - Promising for refractory; (5) **Antiviral therapy** — limited evidence; some use ganciclovir/valganciclovir for EBV PTLD (controversial benefit); (6) **Multidisciplinary**: transplant nephrology, hematology/oncology, ID, surgery (lymph node biopsy diagnostic); (7) **PTLD types (WHO)**: - Early lesions (hyperplastic — plasmacytic hyperplasia, IM-like) — RI usually sufficient - Polymorphic — mixed; usually RI + rituximab - Monomorphic — looks like lymphoma (most often DLBCL, Burkitt-like, plasmacytic); needs chemo - Hodgkin-like - Plasmablastic; (8) **Risk factors** for PTLD: - EBV mismatch (EBV-seronegative recipient + EBV+ donor — high risk) - Pediatric (lower seroprevalence at transplant) - Type of organ (intestine + lung highest risk; kidney lowest) - Intensity of immunosuppression - Use of T-cell depleting induction (ATG, alemtuzumab) — increased risk; (9) **Surveillance**: EBV PCR routine for high-risk (q monthly initially); rising → preemptive RI; (10) **Outcomes**: variable based on subtype + response; mortality 20-50% historically; improving with modern + EBV-CTL therapy"},{"label":"C","text":"Stop all medications"},{"label":"D","text":"Discharge home"},{"label":"E","text":"Surgery only without systemic"}]'::jsonb,
  'B', '**Post-Transplant Lymphoproliferative Disorder (PTLD)** — most common malignancy post-transplant; predominantly B-cell, EBV-driven (~ 70-80% — primary infection or reactivation in immunosuppressed host). **Incidence**: ~ 1-2% kidney, 3-5% liver/heart, 5-10% lung/intestine, 5-15% pediatric. **Risk factors**: EBV mismatch (EBV-naive recipient receiving EBV+ organ — primary infection drives PTLD), pediatric (lower seroprevalence), specific organs (intestine + lung > liver + heart > kidney), intensity of immunosuppression, T-cell depleting agents (ATG, alemtuzumab). **WHO classification**: 1. **Early lesions**: plasmacytic hyperplasia, IM-like — RI often sufficient 2. **Polymorphic PTLD**: mixed B-cell populations 3. **Monomorphic PTLD**: looks like lymphoma — most often DLBCL > Burkitt-like > plasmacytic > others; require lymphoma-like treatment 4. **Classical Hodgkin-like PTLD** **Diagnosis**: biopsy + immunohistochemistry + EBV staining (EBER ISH gold standard); PET-CT staging. **Management — step-wise (treatment intensity individualized to disease)**: 1. **Reduce immunosuppression (RI)** — single most important; restore immune control; balance against rejection; usually reduce CNI 25-50% + stop antimetabolite, maintain steroid 2. **Rituximab (anti-CD20)** — monotherapy for early/limited disease; well-tolerated; risk-adapted approach (Trappe RR2 trial) — rituximab × 4, then assess; responders continue rituximab; non-responders add chemo 3. **R-CHOP** or alternative chemotherapy for: - Poor risk - Bulky - Monomorphic - Refractory - Burkitt-like (DA-EPOCH-R) - Plasmablastic 4. **EBV-specific cytotoxic T lymphocytes (EBV-CTL)** — emerging breakthrough: - Tabelecleucel (third-party allogeneic EBV-CTL bank) — FDA-approved 2024 for EBV-positive PTLD after HCT/SOT - Autologous EBV-CTL (older approach, requires viable patient samples) - Dramatic responses in refractory PTLD 5. **Surgery / RT** — selected for localized; rare 6. **Antiviral** (ganciclovir/valganciclovir) — controversial, mostly adjunct **Surveillance**: EBV PCR monitoring in high-risk (especially EBV-naive recipients first year); rising PCR → preemptive RI or rituximab. **Outcomes**: improving; varies by subtype + response. Pediatric outcomes better than adult monomorphic.', NULL,
  'hard', 'hemato_onco', 'review',
  'surgery', 'clinical_decision', 'hemato_onco', 'adult',
  'AST PTLD Consensus; Trappe RU et al. JCO (PTLD-1); Prockop SE et al. (Tabelecleucel)', 'AI-generated-board-seed', true, 'seeded via Claude Code session (no critique pass)'
from public.mcq_subjects s
where s.name = 'surg_clinical_decision'
  and s.audience = 'board'
  and not exists (
    select 1 from public.mcq_questions q
    where q.exam_source = 'AI-generated-board-seed'
