select
  s.id, 'board', NULL, 'Integrative: chronic post-surgical pain syndrome

คำถาม: chronic pain after surgery — integrative', '[{"label":"A","text":"Opioids alone forever"},{"label":"B","text":"**Chronic post-surgical pain (CPSP) — integrative multimodal management**: (1) **Definition**: persistent pain > 3-6 months post-surgery, beyond expected healing; affects 10-50% of surgical patients depending on procedure; (2) **High-risk procedures**: amputation (phantom + stump pain), thoracotomy, mastectomy, inguinal hernia, cardiac surgery, joint replacement; (3) **Risk factors**: pre-op chronic pain, female, younger age, psychological factors (depression, anxiety, catastrophizing), genetic, severity of acute post-op pain, surgical factors (nerve injury, large incision, hardware); (4) **Mechanisms**: - Neuropathic — nerve injury, neuroma, entrapment, allodynia, hyperalgesia, central sensitization - Nociceptive — ongoing inflammation, mechanical, scar - Mixed; (5) **Prevention strategies (essential — easier to prevent than treat)**: - Multimodal analgesia (see prior question) - Regional anesthesia (epidural, peripheral nerve blocks, local infiltration) - Minimally invasive surgical techniques - Atraumatic tissue handling, nerve preservation - Gabapentinoid perioperative (controversial in recent meta-analyses) - Identify + treat acute post-op pain aggressively - Psychological preparation, expectation setting, education - Optimize pre-op pain conditions - Limit opioid duration; (6) **Assessment of chronic pain**: - Multidimensional (intensity, function, mood, sleep) - Validated tools (BPI, NRS, NPRS, pain catastrophizing, DN4 for neuropathic features) - Diagnostic workup (rule out anatomic — recurrence, mass, mesh issue, neuroma, etc.) - Imaging (MRI for nerve, soft tissue) - Selective nerve blocks (diagnostic + therapeutic); (7) **Treatment — multimodal**: a. **Pharmacologic**: - **Non-opioid first-line**: NSAID, acetaminophen, topical (lidocaine, capsaicin, diclofenac, menthol) - **Neuropathic-targeted**: gabapentin, pregabalin, duloxetine (SNRI), TCA (amitriptyline, nortriptyline) - **Opioids** — last-line for chronic non-cancer pain; if used, careful selection + monitoring + lowest effective dose + multimodal + functional goals + screening; - **Cannabinoids** — emerging, mixed evidence; some chronic pain conditions, legal context dependent b. **Interventional**: - Nerve blocks (diagnostic + therapeutic) - Pulsed radiofrequency ablation - Radiofrequency ablation - Spinal cord stimulator (SCS) — refractory neuropathic - Peripheral nerve stimulator - Intrathecal pump — selected severe c. **Surgical**: - Neurectomy / triple neurectomy (post-hernia) - Neuroma excision - Mesh removal (selected post-hernia) - Hardware removal d. **Physical**: - Physical therapy + tailored exercise - TENS, ice, heat - Manual therapy, massage e. **Psychological**: - CBT for chronic pain - Mindfulness-based stress reduction - Pain neuroscience education - Acceptance + commitment therapy (ACT) f. **Lifestyle**: - Sleep hygiene - Exercise (graded activity) - Weight management - Stress management; (8) **Multidisciplinary pain clinic** — for complex / refractory; (9) **Opioid stewardship**: - Avoid opioid escalation - Risk screening (ORT, SOAPP-R) - PDMP query - Drug monitoring - Naloxone co-prescription if at-risk - Buprenorphine transition for selected; (10) **Patient-centered**: function + quality of life > pain score alone; address whole person"},{"label":"C","text":"Avoid all interventions"},{"label":"D","text":"Single intervention only"},{"label":"E","text":"Discharge without follow-up"}]'::jsonb,
  'B', '**Chronic Post-Surgical Pain (CPSP)** — emerging recognition; common (10-50% varies by procedure); under-recognized + under-treated. **Definition** (IASP): pain persisting > 3 months post-surgery, beyond expected healing, not pre-existing, not explained by other cause. **High-risk procedures**: 1. Amputation (phantom limb + stump pain) — 50-80% 2. Thoracotomy — 30-50% 3. Mastectomy — 20-50% 4. Inguinal hernia repair — 10-15% (severe 1-3%) 5. Cardiac surgery (sternotomy) — 20-30% 6. Joint replacement — 10-20% 7. C-section — 10-15% 8. Cholecystectomy — 5-10% **Risk factors**: - Pre-op: pre-existing chronic pain, female, younger age, depression/anxiety/catastrophizing, genetic, opioid use - Surgical: nerve injury, type of incision, surgical experience, surgery duration - Post-op: severity of acute pain, opioid escalation, complications **Mechanisms**: - Peripheral sensitization (inflammation, neuroplasticity at injury site) - Central sensitization (CNS amplification of pain signals; descending inhibition impaired) - Neuropathic (nerve injury — transection, traction, compression, neuroma) **Prevention** (more effective than treatment): 1. Multimodal analgesia (perioperative) 2. Regional anesthesia (continuous nerve blocks, epidural) reduces CPSP in some studies 3. Minimally invasive surgery 4. Nerve preservation + identification (e.g., hernia surgery — identify all 3 nerves) 5. Gabapentinoid perioperative — controversial; recent meta-analyses + RCTs (Verret M et al — meta-analysis suggests less benefit than previously thought) 6. Aggressive acute pain control 7. Identify + address psychological factors pre-op 8. Limit opioid duration post-op 9. Patient education + expectation setting **Assessment**: multidimensional (intensity, function, mood, sleep, social impact). Validated tools: BPI (Brief Pain Inventory), DN4 (neuropathic features), pain catastrophizing scale, PROMIS measures. **Treatment**: multimodal, multidisciplinary: 1. Non-opioid first-line (NSAID, acetaminophen, topicals) 2. Neuropathic-targeted (gabapentin, pregabalin, duloxetine, TCA) — better evidence for some conditions 3. Interventional (blocks, ablation, SCS, intrathecal) 4. Surgical (neurectomy, neuroma excision, mesh removal, hardware removal) — selected 5. Physical therapy + exercise 6. Psychological (CBT, mindfulness, ACT, pain neuroscience education) 7. Lifestyle 8. Opioids: last-line for chronic non-cancer pain; if used, careful — lowest dose, multimodal, functional goals, monitoring, PDMP, screening, naloxone co-prescription. **Opioid epidemic context**: judicious use post-op, limit duration + supply, educate patients, safe disposal, naloxone for at-risk, address opioid use disorder when present (MAT — methadone, buprenorphine, naltrexone). **Multidisciplinary pain clinic** for complex/refractory.', NULL,
  'medium', 'procedures', 'review',
  'surgery', 'integrative', 'procedures', 'adult',
  'IASP CPSP Definition; Schug SA et al. Br J Anaesth; Kehlet H et al. Lancet', 'AI-generated-board-seed', true, 'seeded via Claude Code session (no critique pass)'
from public.mcq_subjects s
