select
  s.id, 'board', NULL, 'Clinical: orthopedic — open fracture

คำถาม: open fracture management', '[{"label":"A","text":"Discharge home"},{"label":"B","text":"**Open fracture — surgical emergency requires systematic approach**: (1) **Gustilo-Anderson classification**: - **I**: wound < 1 cm, clean, low-energy - **II**: wound > 1 cm without extensive soft tissue damage - **IIIA**: extensive soft tissue but coverage possible - **IIIB**: extensive soft tissue loss + bone exposure requiring coverage (flap) - **IIIC**: vascular injury requiring repair; (2) **Management**: a. **Emergency Department**: - ATLS primary + secondary survey - **IV antibiotic ASAP** (within 1 hour, ideally < 3 hr of injury — strongest evidence base): - Type I-II: cefazolin (1st-gen cephalosporin) - Type III: cefazolin + aminoglycoside (gentamicin); add penicillin for farm/soil contamination (Clostridium); add fluoroquinolone or 3rd-gen cephalosporin alternative - Newer studies: cefazolin alone may be sufficient even for III in selected; tailored antibiogram - **Tetanus** immunization status + booster ± Tig (immunoglobulin) if high-risk - **Photograph wound** + cover with saline-soaked sterile dressing - **Splint** + immobilize - **Pre-op labs + radiographs** + appropriate imaging - Type & cross b. **Operative management — time-sensitive**: - **Irrigation + debridement (I&D)** within 24h (older 6h dogma less supported by recent evidence — FLOW trial; antibiotic timing more important than I&D timing per LEAP + others); urgent for severely contaminated, vascular compromise, compartment syndrome - I&D: copious irrigation (low-pressure NS preferred — FLOW trial NEJM 2015; antiseptic additive controversial), thorough debridement of devitalized tissue + foreign body - **Fracture stabilization**: external fixation initially for severe contamination → conversion to internal fixation when wound healed; primary internal fixation for less contaminated; nailing for shaft - **Repeat I&D** q24-48h until wound clean - **Soft tissue coverage** — primary closure if clean + tension-free; otherwise wound VAC + delayed primary closure OR flap (local, regional, free) within 3-7 days (Godina principle); c. **Wound infection** common — Pseudomonas + MRSA risk; cultures + antibiotic stewardship d. **Compartment syndrome** surveillance — fasciotomy if pressure elevated + symptoms; e. **Limb salvage vs amputation** — MESS score (Mangled Extremity Severity Score) + clinical judgment; LEAP study showed similar functional outcomes long-term salvage vs amputation in selected severe injuries; multidisciplinary; (3) **Specific concerns**: - **Vascular injury** (Type IIIC) — vascular surgery + repair before bony stabilization (shunt + stabilize + then bypass); - **Open joint** — copious irrigation + early antibiotic + closure - **Mangled extremity** — multidisciplinary (vascular, ortho, plastics, trauma); patient-centered decision about salvage vs amputation; (4) **Long-term**: - Functional rehabilitation - Psychological - Pain management - Nonunion + malunion management - Late infection - Hardware-related issues; (5) **Prevention** of complications: early IV antibiotic (within 3h ideal), prompt I&D (within 24h), appropriate fixation, soft tissue coverage (early flap if needed), surveillance + early intervention"},{"label":"C","text":"Outpatient antibiotic only"},{"label":"D","text":"Observation 48 hr"},{"label":"E","text":"Steroid alone"}]'::jsonb,
  'B', '**Open fracture management** — orthopedic surgical emergency; principles aim to prevent infection (osteomyelitis) + preserve function. **Gustilo-Anderson classification** — guides management + prognosis: - **I**: < 1 cm, clean, low-energy - **II**: > 1 cm, moderate soft tissue damage - **III**: extensive soft tissue or high-energy; subdivided: - IIIA: adequate soft tissue coverage available - IIIB: bone exposure + flap coverage needed - IIIC: vascular injury requiring repair **Key principles**: 1. **IV antibiotic ASAP** — strongest evidence (within 1 hour, ideally < 3 hr); cefazolin (I-II); cefazolin + aminoglycoside (III) — though newer studies suggest cefazolin alone may suffice in many; tailor to wound + local antibiogram. Penicillin/metronidazole for farm/soil contamination (Clostridium). 2. **Tetanus**: status + booster ± Tig 3. **I&D timing**: classic ''6-hour rule'' less evidence-based per modern data (FLOW + LEAP + others); within 24h acceptable + may not change outcomes; urgent if severe contamination, vascular compromise, compartment syndrome 4. **Irrigation** — low-pressure NS preferred (FLOW NEJM 2015 — high-pressure no advantage + may push bacteria deeper; antiseptic additives no benefit) 5. **Debridement** — all devitalized tissue + foreign body; assess viability; repeat as needed 6. **Fracture stabilization**: external fixation initially for severe; convert to internal when clean; primary internal in selected (less contaminated, fresh) 7. **Soft tissue coverage**: primary closure if clean + tension-free; otherwise wound VAC + delayed primary closure OR flap (Godina principle — early flap improves outcomes; within 72h ideal in tibial fractures) — local, regional, free flap by reconstructive plastic surgery 8. **Infection surveillance** + treatment **Compartment syndrome** — major concern: - 6 P''s: pain disproportionate, pallor, paresthesia, paralysis, pulselessness (late), poikilothermia - Pain with passive stretch most sensitive - Compartment pressures > 30 mmHg or within 30 of diastolic = positive - Fasciotomy emergent **Mangled extremity** + decisions about salvage vs amputation: - **MESS score** + clinical judgment - LEAP study — long-term functional outcomes similar for salvage vs amputation in selected severe lower extremity injuries - Patient + multidisciplinary input - Quality of life considerations **Vascular injury** (IIIC) — vascular repair priority; shunt for distal perfusion while orthopedic stabilization, then definitive bypass. **Long-term outcomes**: pain, function, return to work, psychological all important; rehabilitation + multidisciplinary; chronic osteomyelitis significant risk despite optimal management; PTSD common in major extremity injury patients (especially combat-related).', NULL,
  'medium', 'trauma', 'review',
  'surgery', 'clinical_decision', 'trauma', 'adult',
  'EAST Open Fracture Guidelines; LEAP Study; Bhandari M et al. NEJM 2015 (FLOW)', 'AI-generated-board-seed', true, 'seeded via Claude Code session (no critique pass)'
from public.mcq_subjects s
where s.name = 'surg_clinical_decision'
