select
  s.id, 'board', NULL, 'Clinical: surgical infection — necrotizing pancreatitis evolution

คำถาม: walled-off pancreatic necrosis management', '[{"label":"A","text":"Immediate open necrosectomy"},{"label":"B","text":"**Walled-off pancreatic necrosis (WOPN) — step-up approach (PANTER paradigm)**: (1) **Wait for walled-off necrosis** — typically 4+ weeks from onset of pancreatitis: - WOPN is encapsulated collection of necrotic tissue + fluid - Allows safer intervention than early intervention (less bleeding + sepsis); (2) **Infected vs sterile necrosis**: - Sterile necrosis: no intervention unless symptomatic / complications (gastric outlet obstruction, biliary obstruction, persistent symptoms, expanding) - Infected necrosis: needs intervention; signs — clinical decline, gas in necrosis on CT, positive FNA culture, persistent organ dysfunction; (3) **Step-up approach (PANTER trial NEJM 2010 — van Santvoort)**: - **Step 1**: percutaneous catheter drainage (PCD) — IR-guided through retroperitoneum (left flank preferred — avoids contamination + facilitates later sinus tract for endoscopic/minimally invasive necrosectomy) - **Step 2**: minimally invasive necrosectomy if step 1 inadequate at 4-7 days: - Video-assisted retroperitoneal debridement (VARD) - Endoscopic transgastric necrosectomy (multiple sessions; cystgastrostomy + repeated debridement) - Laparoscopic transgastric/transmesenteric - Sinus tract endoscopy via PCD tract - **Step 3**: open necrosectomy — last resort for failed minimally invasive (rare in modern era); (4) **Endoscopic approach (TENSION trial Lancet 2018)** — endoscopic step-up: lumen-apposing metal stent (LAMS — Hot AXIOS) cystgastrostomy → DEN (direct endoscopic necrosectomy) sessions; comparable outcomes to surgical step-up with less new-onset organ failure; growing preferred approach for WOPN amenable; (5) **Modern combined / hybrid approaches**: - Dual modality (endo + percutaneous) for complex disease - Tailored by anatomy + location of necrosis - Multidisciplinary team essential; (6) **Indications for intervention** (not all necrosis needs it): - Infected necrosis (clinical, gas on CT, positive FNA) - Persistent symptoms (failure to progress with diet, persistent pain, GOO) - Complications (bleeding from pseudoaneurysm — IR embolization first; mass effect on adjacent organs) - Sterile necrosis usually NOT intervened (improved with conservative + supportive); (7) **Adjuncts**: - Nutritional support — early enteral (NJ or NG); TPN if not feasible - Pain management - Pancreatic enzyme replacement if EPI develops - Treat underlying (gallstone — cholecystectomy + ERCP, alcohol — cessation) - Glycemic control - Antibiotic if infected — broad-spectrum + culture-directed (carbapenem penetrates pancreatic tissue well); (8) **Outcomes**: step-up approach reduces new organ failure + mortality (~ 16% vs 31% open in PANTER) + LOS + costs; endoscopic step-up further reduces new organ failure; (9) **Long-term**: pancreatic insufficiency (exocrine + endocrine) common; PERT + DM management; survivorship care including imaging surveillance for pancreatic cancer (slightly elevated risk in chronic pancreatitis)"},{"label":"C","text":"Observation indefinitely"},{"label":"D","text":"Sorafenib"},{"label":"E","text":"Liver transplant"}]'::jsonb,
  'B', '**Walled-off Pancreatic Necrosis (WOPN)** — late complication of necrotizing pancreatitis; encapsulated collection of necrosis + fluid; typically forms by 4+ weeks. **Distinction from acute necrotic collection (ANC, < 4 weeks)** + pseudocyst (no solid necrotic content) + acute peripancreatic fluid collection (APFC). Atlanta 2012 classification. **Management paradigm shift** — from early aggressive open necrosectomy (high mortality ~ 30-50%) → delayed step-up approach (lower mortality ~ 5-20% modern series). **PANTER trial (van Santvoort et al, NEJM 2010)** — landmark: - Step-up: PCD → MIS necrosectomy as needed - Open: traditional approach - Results: step-up reduced new-onset multi-organ failure + complications (without mortality difference; subsequent updates suggest mortality benefit); set standard for management **TENSION trial (van Brunschot et al, Lancet 2018)** — endoscopic step-up vs surgical step-up: - Endoscopic step-up (LAMS cystgastrostomy + DEN) reduced new organ failure (vs surgical step-up) - Similar mortality - Less pancreatic fistulas - Less ICU stay - Endoscopic approach growing in centers with expertise **Step-up approach steps**: 1. **Wait** for walled-off (4+ weeks) unless infected + decompensating 2. **Percutaneous drainage** first — IR-guided; retroperitoneal route preferred (left flank — avoids peritoneal contamination + creates sinus tract for later interventions) 3. **Antibiotic** if infected (carbapenem — meropenem, imipenem — penetrate pancreatic tissue well; fluoroquinolone alternative) 4. **Minimally invasive necrosectomy** if percutaneous inadequate at 4-7 days: - VARD (video-assisted retroperitoneal debridement) - Endoscopic transgastric (LAMS cystgastrostomy + DEN) - Laparoscopic transgastric - Sinus tract endoscopy 5. **Open necrosectomy** — last resort; rare in modern centers **Indications for intervention**: 1. Infected necrosis (clinical, gas on CT, positive FNA) 2. Persistent symptoms (pain, GOO, failure to progress) 3. Complications (bleeding pseudoaneurysm — IR embolization first; mass effect) Sterile necrosis usually NOT intervened — better with supportive. **Bleeding pseudoaneurysm** — major mortality contributor in pancreatitis: visceral aneurysm in inflamed area; IR angio + embolization first-line; surgery if failed. **Long-term sequelae**: - Pancreatic exocrine insufficiency — PERT - Pancreatic endocrine (type 3c DM) - Pseudocyst (residual) - Chronic pancreatitis - Strictures (biliary, GI) - Pancreatic cancer slightly elevated risk - Quality of life impact substantial.', NULL,
  'hard', 'gi', 'review',
  'surgery', 'clinical_decision', 'gi', 'adult',
  'PANTER van Santvoort HC et al. NEJM 2010; TENSION van Brunschot S et al. Lancet 2018; WSES Severe Acute Pancreatitis 2019', 'AI-generated-board-seed', true, 'seeded via Claude Code session (no critique pass)'
from public.mcq_subjects s
